section.p:
Figuring out how to perform calculations with continuous compounding requires limits.  We will need to make use of L'HĮpital's Rule.  This tells us that if the limit of a quotient of functions is indeterminate: 

	\lim_{x \rightarrow a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \frac{\infty}{\infty}, \ \mbox{or} \ \frac{0}{0}

then the limit is equal to the limit of the quotient of the derivatives (if it exists): 

	\lim_{x \rightarrow a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \lim_{x \rightarrow a}\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}
